Question 1. Weekly vs Monthly Exploratory Data Analysis (20 points)

1a. Based on your intuition, when would you use weekly instead of monthly time series data?

Response

When we have both the weekly and monthly data available, the weekly time series would be used for a more granular analysis, specifically, when the short term changes are of more relevance. In cases where the data fluctuates quickly (high volatility), we would prefer to gauge the variance in these observations. The disadvantage of using the weekly data versus monthly data would be introducing more variability than needed when less granular analysis (e.g. monthly predictions) is of interest.

Response: Weekly vs Montly Time Series data comparison

The time series data consist of a little over 10 years for CNY and JPY, both on a weekly and monthly basis. We can clearly see that the monthly data is just a smoothed version of the weekly data. For the Chinese Yuan exchange rate, there is no clear seasonality in the time series, but the trend fluctuates greatly over time. Similarly, for the Japanese Yen exchange rate, there is no clear seasonality in the time series but there is a trend which decreases between 2010 and 2012, then increases and fluctuates but remains relatively higher than at the beginning of the time period.

num <- 8

norder <- num
p <- 1:norder - 1
q <- 1:norder - 1
aic <- matrix(0, norder, norder) 
for (i in 1:norder) {
for (j in 1:norder) {
modij = arima(CNY.w.train,
                  order = c(p[i], 1, q[j]),
                  method = 'ML')
    aic[i, j] = modij$aic - 2 * (p[i] + q[j] + 1) + 2 * (p[i] + q[j] + 1) *
      n / (n - p[i] - q[j] - 2)
  }
}

Response: Analysis of the ARIMA Fit for the Weekly and Monthly Data

The selected models for the weekly data are as follows:

  • CNY Model Selection: ARIMA(7,1,7) with AICc = -2863.87 vs ARIMA(6,2,4) with AICc = -2850.528. We will select ARIMA(7,1,7) as the optimal model.
  • JPY Model Selection: ARIMA(4,1,5) with AICc = 1781.601 vs ARIMA(0,2,2) with AICc = 1788.179, with the ARIMA(4,1,5) having a lower AICc value hence selected.

In order to evaluate whether a reduced order for AR or MA will result in a less complex model but with similar explanatory power, we can evaluate the p-value of the z-test for statistical significance of the coefficients corresponding to the highest AR or MA order. Below, I am providing a simple p-value function that can be used to compute the p-values of the z-tests for all coefficients.

## p-value function for the z-test taking as input the test statistic
pvalue.coef <- function(tv){ 2*(1-pnorm(abs(tv)))
}
## compute the test statistics
tv.CNY.weekly <-as.numeric(final_model$coef)/as.numeric(sqrt(diag(final_model$var.coef)))
tv.JPY.weekly <-as.numeric(final_model_JPY$coef)/as.numeric(sqrt(diag(final_model_JPY$var.coef)))
## Apply the pvalue.coef function
pvalues.CNY.weekly <- sapply(tv.CNY.weekly, pvalue.coef)
pvalues.JPY.weekly <- sapply(tv.JPY.weekly, pvalue.coef)
print("CNY T Values:")
## [1] "CNY T Values:"
print(tv.CNY.weekly)

Response: Statistical Significance

The z-tests for the models’ coefficients show that at the \(\alpha = .05\) significance level, four of the AR coefficients and four of the MA coefficients for the weekly CNY model and one of the AR coefficients for the weekly JPY model are not significant. Thus, lower orders may be preferable to use for both models.

2b. Evaluate the model residuals using the ACF and PACF plots, the residual plot and residuals’ histogram as well as hypothesis testing for serial correlation for the selected models in (2a) for the two currencies. Does the model fit the time series data? Compare the model fit for the two currency exchange rates.

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
# CNY Residuals
resids <- resid(final_model)
plot(resids,
     ylab = 'Residuals',
     type = 'o',
     main = "Residual Plot")
abline(h = 0)
hist(resids, xlab = 'Residuals', main = 'Histogram: Residuals')
acf(resids, main = "CNY ACF: Residuals")
pacf(resids, main = "CNY PACF: Residuals")

Box.test(
  final_model$resid,
  lag = (porder_1 + qorder_1 + 1),
  type = "Box-Pierce",
  fitdf = (porder_1 + qorder_1)
)
## 
##  Box-Pierce test
## 
## data:  final_model$resid
## X-squared = 7.3899, df = 1, p-value = 0.006559
Box.test(
  final_model$resid,
  lag = (porder_1 + qorder_1 + 1),
  type = "Ljung-Box",
   fitdf = (porder_1 + qorder_1)
)
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  final_model$resid
## X-squared = 7.4959, df = 1, p-value = 0.006184
# JPY Residuals

acf(resids, main = "JPY ACF: Residuals")
pacf(resids, main = "JPY PACF: Residuals")

Box.test(

Response: Residual Analysis

The fit for the JPY data seems to be somewhat better fitting as assessed using the residual plots. The ACF and PACF plots resemble those of white noise. The plots for the CNY data show some heteroskedasticity in the residuals, as well as lags outside of the confidence bands.

Serial correlation testing results: The null hypothesis is that the residual process consists of uncorrelated variables. which is supported since the p-values are larger than 0.05. The p-values for the JPY data are not significant at this level, so we fail to reject the null hypothesis in this case. The tests for the CNY data, however, show evidence of serial correlation in the residual process.

Response: Prediction Accuracy

All the observations are within the prediction bands for both the models. However, the model for CNY seems to be a better fit since both the MAPE and the PM measures are lower. However, both models do not seem to provide good predictions since the variability in the predictions is much higher than the variability in the data (i.e. very high PM values).

                  order = c(p[i], 1, q[j]),
method = 'ML')
    aic[i, j] = modij$aic - 2 * (p[i] + q[j] + 1) + 2 * (p[i] + q[j] + 1) *
      n / (n - p[i] - q[j] - 2)
  }
}
# Extract the "best" one according to AIC
aicv <- as.vector(aic)
plot(aicv, ylab = "AIC values")

indexp <- rep(c(1:norder), norder)
indexq <- rep(c(1:norder), each = norder)
indexaic <- which(aicv == min(aicv))
porder_5 <- indexp[indexaic] - 1
qorder_5 <- indexq[indexaic] - 1
# Fit the "best" arima model
m_final_model <-
  arima(CNY.m.train,
        order = c(porder_5, 1, qorder_5),
        method = "ML")

Response: Analysis of the ARIMA Fit for the Weekly and Monthly Data

The selected models for the weekly data are as follows:

  • CNY Model Selection: ARIMA(4,1,3) with AICc = -372.856 vs ARIMA(5,2,4) with AICc = -361.496, where the less complex model ARIMA(4,1,3) model has a smaller AICc value.
  • JPY Model Selection: ARIMA(2,1,2) with AICc = 650.551 vs ARIMA(2,2,1) with AICc = 653.676, with the ARIMA(2,1,2) having a lower AICc value hence selected.

In order to evaluate whether a reduced order for AR or MA will result in a less complex model but with similar explanatory power, we can evaluate the p-value of the z-test for statistical significance of the coefficients corresponding to the highest AR or MA order. Applying a similar procedure as in previous question, we find that all p-values are approximately zero for the JPY model, suggesting that this model should not be reduced further. The CNY model, however, has one AR coefficient and two MA coefficients which are not significant at the \(\alpha=.05\) significance level, so reducing it may be beneficial.

Response: Monthly vs Weekly Data

  • CNY: Monthly model ARIMA(4,1,3) vs Weekly model ARIMA(7,1,7)
  • JPY Monthly model ARIMA(2,1,2) vs Weekly model ARIMA(4,1,5)

Hence the monthly models are less complex for both exchange rates.

Question 5. Reflection on ARIMA (5 points)

Considering your understanding of the ARIMA model in general as well as what your understanding of the behavior of the currency exchange data based on the completion of the above questions, how would you personally regard the effectiveness of ARIMA modelling? Where would it be appropriate to use it for forecasting and where would you recommend against? What are some specific points of caution one would need to consider when considering using it?

Response: Reflection on ARIMA

ARIMA can be a useful tool to analyze time series which can be detrended by differencing. The ARIMA fit the two time series appropriately for both currencies. While the models are good fit, the predictions are poorly capturing the increasing trend. This suggests that a model that would first fit and predict the trend would perform better than the ARIMA model. We also learn that for such time series, we only can perform short term predictions.

The (simple) ARIMA model has other limitations, for example, doesn’t include external factors influencing the variation in the time series, which can be accounted in the extension of ARIMA, called ARIMAX.

Note: The response to this question will vary from one student to another!
